WEBVTT

00:00.770 --> 00:04.315
Hello friends, I'm Rick Warren, and welcome to Spurgeon's Sermons.

00:04.775 --> 00:09.522
This is the official podcast brought to you by Premier and Spurgeon's College.

00:10.183 --> 00:18.354
You know the teachings of Charles Spurgeon have had a personal impact on my life in a profound way, and I'm confident they'll do the same for you.

00:18.474 --> 00:27.747
So get ready to be challenged, equipped, and guided by Charles Spurgeon, who is universally regarded as the greatest English preacher in the history of the church.

00:29.249 --> 00:30.130
The heroic

00:30.338 --> 00:35.523
in Christianity, a sermon by Charles Spurgeon, part three.

00:35.543 --> 00:40.948
For if ye love them which love you, what thank have ye?

00:41.008 --> 00:44.231
For sinners also love those that love them.

00:44.271 --> 00:50.317
And if ye do good to them which do good to you, what thank have ye?

00:50.357 --> 00:53.160
For sinners also do even the same.

00:53.200 --> 00:59.986
And if ye lend to them of whom ye hope to receive, what thank have ye?

01:00.674 --> 01:04.898
for sinners also lend to sinners to receive as much again.

01:06.179 --> 01:09.603
Luke's Gospel, chapter 6, verses 32 to 34.

01:10.604 --> 01:17.771
Followers of Jesus are called upon to do good to those who have done them harm.

01:18.892 --> 01:29.682
You know the old saying, evil for good is devil-like, evil for evil is beast-like, good for good is man-like,

01:30.370 --> 01:33.213
Good for evil is God-like.

01:34.474 --> 01:36.776
Rise you to that God-like point.

01:37.937 --> 01:45.364
If a man has taken the bread out of your mouth, seize the first opportunity to help him to a livelihood.

01:46.345 --> 01:49.808
If he has bespattered you, be ready to forgive him.

01:50.709 --> 01:52.611
But say not a word against him.

01:53.492 --> 02:00.178
Watch for a time when, by great kindness, you may heap coals of fire on his head.

02:01.058 --> 02:08.828
Hard teaching says one, I know it is, and harder doing, but it is blessed doing.

02:09.749 --> 02:12.572
It is sweet to render good for ill.

02:13.633 --> 02:20.342
There is a self-conquest about it which ennobles the soul more than the conquest of an empire.

02:22.044 --> 02:30.354
There is a getting near to Christ in such actions that hath about it more of heaven than all beside.

02:31.618 --> 02:46.359
that patient persevering rendering of benefits for injuries, returning a favor for enmity, gives us fellowship with him who, when we were enemies, laid down his life for us.

02:47.901 --> 02:53.610
O taste this sweet grace of forgiveness, and see if it be not good.

02:55.052 --> 02:59.378
If you have never known Christian joy, you shall know it then.

03:00.322 --> 03:07.470
It is a high virtue, nevertheless, to this we must come if we are to be the followers of Christ.

03:09.613 --> 03:27.634
Again, you note in the 34th verse that mention is made of helping others in a neighborly way, with the expectation of their returning the friendly deed, if ye lend to them of whom ye hope to receive, what thank have ye.

03:28.034 --> 03:37.288
is often rendered in the expectation that if ever we are in the same need, we shall only need to ask and receive like aid.

03:38.250 --> 03:42.636
I lend you an axe, and you will one day lend me a sore.

03:43.518 --> 03:47.544
You borrow my pale, and you will lend me your flat iron.

03:48.846 --> 03:53.553
Enable a sort of barter which goes on all around and ought to go on.

03:54.475 --> 03:56.658
But there is nothing very wonderful in it.

03:56.962 --> 04:03.569
For after all, it is a sort of laying-by-in store, making your neighbor your banker for a while.

04:04.911 --> 04:13.120
I help you, and you help me, a very proper thing to do, and the more of such brotherly and neighborly cooperation, the better.

04:14.021 --> 04:16.764
But still, there is nothing so very virtuous in it.

04:17.645 --> 04:23.371
What thank have you, for sinners also lend to sinners to receive as much again?

04:23.431 --> 04:26.034
You as a Christian,

04:26.370 --> 04:28.793
are to rise to something higher than this.

04:29.895 --> 04:34.361
Namely to be ready to help without the expectation of being helped again.

04:34.421 --> 04:43.614
Ready to aid those who you are certain could not help you, who are too poor ever to come to your rescue.

04:44.555 --> 04:54.930
I am ready to help those who would not help you if they could, who may even return your kindness with words of falsehood and acts of unkindness.

04:55.682 --> 04:57.144
Can you rise to this?

04:58.345 --> 04:59.967
For this is to be a Christian.

05:00.808 --> 05:22.431
This is to be like your heavenly Father, who sends his reign upon the just and upon the unjust, who causes his son to shine upon the field of the brute, as well as upon the garden of the liberal, who gives and gives and gives and receives nothing in return.

05:23.612 --> 05:25.234
It is the glory of God

05:25.538 --> 05:40.259
that He is too great, too full, too glorious to be dependent upon us, an ever-flowing fountain pouring forth incalculable torrents of infinite blessing upon the sons of men.

05:41.921 --> 05:44.505
After our measure, we are to be the same.

05:44.905 --> 05:53.778
We are to aspire to the higher happiness of which our Lord said, it is more blessed to give than to receive.

05:54.978 --> 06:04.287
Here is the dignity, the heavenliness of happiness, not to be receiving from others, but to be freely distributing to them.

06:05.488 --> 06:11.774
May God help us to imitate our God in doing good, hoping for nothing again.

06:11.795 --> 06:23.506
Thus, brethren, I think I have shown you that there are certain good things in the world which nevertheless do not reach to the standard of Christian virtue.

06:24.866 --> 06:28.049
this holds good in all religious actions.

06:29.531 --> 06:35.117
You are known to be a religious man, so were a great many who have turned out to be rogues.

06:36.238 --> 06:39.382
You are a deacon or other church officer.

06:40.022 --> 06:46.049
Yes, so were certain bank directors, who were none the more honest for that.

06:47.310 --> 06:54.418
But you are a preacher, yes, and so was Judas, who hanged himself, and so went to his own place.

06:55.490 --> 07:01.238
Religious acts count for nothing unless there is a true heart at the back of them.

07:02.440 --> 07:09.089
These things ought we to have done, but if we leave hard work undone, nothing is done.

07:10.671 --> 07:24.210
Sinners also perform their religious acts, and besides these, some of them exhibit many external virtues, and yet they manifestly fail to approach the standard of Christian virtue.

07:25.442 --> 07:35.937
The road is the same, and men and women may travel in it apparently in the same direction, and yet they may be journeying with totally different motives.

07:37.038 --> 07:39.241
The first may be on the king's business.

07:40.243 --> 07:42.306
The next may be a footpad.

07:43.287 --> 07:46.692
And the third and escaped convict running from justice.

07:48.014 --> 07:54.002
The same thing may be done by a hundred different people and apparently done in the self-same way.

07:54.978 --> 08:04.389
and yet only one of them may be doing it in God's way and doing it with the sincere motive of honoring and glorifying God.

08:05.390 --> 08:18.925
The 99, though studiously aiming to make the outward action correct, may nevertheless fail as to acceptance with God because their motive and spirit are altogether wrong.

08:20.247 --> 08:23.250
Oh, it shames me when I sit down and look over my life

08:23.554 --> 08:26.618
and inquire, is this a life a Christian ought to live?

08:27.860 --> 08:30.563
Does not the same question arise in your minds?

08:31.985 --> 08:36.952
Do you not feel in many points that unconverted people have excelled you?

08:36.972 --> 08:45.863
Do you not know some persons who are no Christians who are nevertheless more patient than you in the endurance of pain?

08:47.305 --> 08:50.930
Do you not know unbelievers who are generous to a high degree?

08:51.330 --> 08:55.436
and show much of self-sacrifice in helping their poor neighbors.

08:56.939 --> 09:02.728
Do you not know men whose devotion to science is greater than your devotion to Christ?

09:04.090 --> 09:10.239
Are there not within your knowledge persons who have loved their country better than you have loved your Lord?

09:11.601 --> 09:15.067
Do not these thoughts provoke you to something better?

09:16.328 --> 09:19.954
They make me blush and cause my heart to weep.

09:21.154 --> 09:23.417
What manner of person ought I to be?

09:24.098 --> 09:35.051
When those who do not profess to know the mysteries of everlasting love rise to such courage in battle, such endurance in pushing overseas of ice.

09:36.552 --> 09:41.578
What ought I to become when my Lord calls me to be His disciple indeed?

09:43.100 --> 09:45.323
Where are the fruits of my discipleship?

09:46.124 --> 09:47.986
What am I doing to bring Him honor?

09:49.058 --> 10:00.572
If even a text like this staggers me, and I say it is a hard lesson, where, where must I be in the sight of God who sees all my failures?

10:01.874 --> 10:12.107
Secondly, dear friends, I want you to notice that Christian virtue is in many respects extraordinary and might be called heroic.

10:13.729 --> 10:17.874
To illustrate this, I will confine myself to the gospel according to Luke.

10:18.786 --> 10:26.574
In the passage that we have been reading, we have evidently a form of virtue which is quite out of the ordinary range of men's thoughts.

10:27.455 --> 10:28.736
It concerns love.

10:30.018 --> 10:31.359
Love your enemies.

10:32.040 --> 10:37.666
Do good to them that hate you, and pray for them which despitefully use you.

10:38.867 --> 10:45.874
In the point of love, kindness, consideration for men's needs, and desire to do good.

10:46.402 --> 10:51.611
The Christian life is to rise above every other till it becomes sublime.

10:52.933 --> 10:59.584
Heath and moralists recommended kindness, but they did not suggest it's being lavished upon enemies.

11:01.487 --> 11:04.873
I have been somewhat amused by the caution of Cicero.

11:05.434 --> 11:12.626
He says, kindness must not be shown to a youth, nor to an old man, not to the aged.

11:12.994 --> 11:22.547
because he is likely to die before he can have an occasion to repay you the benefit, and not to the young man, for he is sure to forget it.

11:24.329 --> 11:39.730
Those of us who are middle-aged may value the orator's generosity as we like, but we may reflect that he only recommends its exercise towards us because we are likely to be good debtors and payback

11:40.066 --> 11:42.870
what we receive, perhaps with interest.

11:44.432 --> 11:51.000
That gentle laugh which ripples over the congregation is the best refutation of such bear-faced selfishness.

11:52.382 --> 12:00.392
Our Lord bids us seek no reward from men and women, and He assures us that a greater reward will come.

12:01.553 --> 12:04.537
We shall by shunning it secure it.

12:05.598 --> 12:08.562
We shall find a reward in being unrewarded.

12:09.602 --> 12:11.324
see how our Lord puts it.

12:12.346 --> 12:26.704
When thou makeest a dinner or a supper, call not thy friends, nor thy brethren, neither thy kinsmen, nor thy rich neighbors, lest they also bid thee again, and a recompense be made thee.

12:28.246 --> 12:37.778
But when thou makeest a feast, call the poor, the maimed, the lame, and the blind, and thou shalt be blessed.

12:38.690 --> 12:46.018
for they cannot recompense thee, for thou shalt be recompensed at the resurrection of the just."

12:48.240 --> 12:53.746
Next, read Luke's Gospel, chapter 9, verses 54 and 55.

12:55.669 --> 13:01.175
And you will see that the Christian is to rise above human passion in the matter of gentleness.

13:02.376 --> 13:07.922
James and John, when Christ was not received by the Samaritan villagers, said,

13:08.290 --> 13:12.994
Wilt thou that we command fire to come down from heaven and consume them?

13:14.316 --> 13:20.742
But Jesus rebuked them and said, You know not what manner of spirit ye are of.

13:22.003 --> 13:23.544
And they went to another village.

13:25.046 --> 13:30.271
A Christian should be ready to give way he should be quiet, peaceable, gentle.

13:31.652 --> 13:38.098
If in trying to do good he wishes to bless certain people and they refuse to hear him,

13:38.850 --> 13:43.215
Let him not grow indignant and denounce the offenders.

13:44.237 --> 13:50.604
But let him change the scene and carry his message to those who perhaps are hungering for it.

13:51.626 --> 13:57.853
He may go round again very shortly to those who repulsed him and find them in a better mind.

13:59.195 --> 14:00.496
Be gentle, brother.

14:01.397 --> 14:04.021
Soft words are hard to answer.

14:05.102 --> 14:06.604
They refused you at first.

14:07.545 --> 14:08.466
Try them again.

14:09.154 --> 14:13.540
At any rate, be not provoked, for then they will have conquered you.

14:15.222 --> 14:18.247
Christians ought to be the gentlest beings under heaven.

14:19.889 --> 14:25.517
They are sent forth as lambs among wolves, and they are called to be harmless as doves.

14:26.698 --> 14:35.090
Such meekness will astonish and amaze their adversaries and crown the religion of Jesus with honor.

14:37.058 --> 14:38.362
Thank you for listening, friends.

14:38.663 --> 14:44.018
This podcast was brought to you by Premier in association with Spurgeon's College.

14:44.038 --> 14:52.082
